1
00:00:00,458 --> 00:00:02,875
Interviewer: After you stayed 38 days

2
00:00:03,375 --> 00:00:06,875
Of which 28 days were in solitary and alone

3
00:00:06,958 --> 00:00:08,958
And that was the hardest period you went through

4
00:00:09,083 --> 00:00:10,125
Yes, it was

5
00:00:12,125 --> 00:00:15,708
Interviewer: How did you become after this experience?

6
00:00:16,125 --> 00:00:20,708
Was your life after release the same as it was before prison?

7
00:00:20,833 --> 00:00:23,750
Was your personality the same before and after prison?

8
00:00:23,833 --> 00:00:25,416
Or did your life change?

9
00:00:28,958 --> 00:00:31,333
I became cautious in everything

10
00:00:32,125 --> 00:00:35,125
In my movements, in my words, in everything

11
00:00:36,458 --> 00:00:40,000
I even started praying right on time

12
00:00:41,250 --> 00:00:42,708
When the muezzin says Allahu Akbar

13
00:00:42,708 --> 00:00:46,333
I go straight to the mosque, because of fear

14
00:00:48,208 --> 00:00:52,250
Interviewer: Did you have psychological changes?

15
00:00:52,333 --> 00:00:55,708
For example, you were not quick to anger before

16
00:00:55,708 --> 00:00:57,625
Did you become quick to anger?

17
00:00:57,708 --> 00:01:00,958
I had a psychological problem and because of it I still see a psychiatrist

18
00:01:01,083 --> 00:01:02,625
His name is Dr. Ali Neamat

19
00:01:03,583 --> 00:01:05,416
Interviewer: Because of this detention?
Witness: Yes, because of it

20
00:01:05,458 --> 00:01:08,083
And until now I take psychiatric medication

21
00:01:08,500 --> 00:01:10,375
Interviewer: How was your condition at the beginning?

22
00:01:10,458 --> 00:01:12,416
Surely your condition now is not like it was at the beginning

23
00:01:12,541 --> 00:01:13,958
So how was your condition at the beginning?

24
00:01:13,958 --> 00:01:20,416
Did you feel that your interactions were easy with your wife, children, and people?

25
00:01:20,708 --> 00:01:24,625
Or were you withdrawn and afraid of everyone?

26
00:01:24,958 --> 00:01:28,833
Did you become more afraid for your children, that the same thing might happen to them?

27
00:01:28,875 --> 00:01:30,583
I want you to describe that state you were in

28
00:01:30,708 --> 00:01:35,750
Before prison I was normal and had no problem

29
00:01:36,250 --> 00:01:39,458
But after prison I developed this psychological problem

30
00:01:40,625 --> 00:01:45,125
I was irritable with my family, my wife, and my kids

31
00:01:46,375 --> 00:01:50,958
And when ISIS was present my anger was mixed with fear

32
00:01:51,083 --> 00:01:54,083
I feared that if I raised my voice they would hear it, because they walked right by the door

33
00:01:54,958 --> 00:01:56,458
Interviewer: Did you feel you were being watched?

34
00:01:57,125 --> 00:01:58,250
Yes, I felt I was being watched

35
00:01:58,875 --> 00:02:02,000
Interviewer: Were you not comfortable with your actions and movements even in your home?

36
00:02:02,458 --> 00:02:04,458
Yes, because I developed a psychological problem

37
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:07,250
A severe psychological problem until now

38
00:02:07,583 --> 00:02:15,375
Interviewer: Your relationships with people, trust in them, and new relationships

39
00:02:15,458 --> 00:02:18,958
Were they the same as they used to be?

40
00:02:19,125 --> 00:02:22,875
In making decisions with people or with a specific person

41
00:02:23,333 --> 00:02:27,458
Was it the same thinking and same feeling?

42
00:02:27,833 --> 00:02:29,458
No, I’ve become different now

43
00:02:29,708 --> 00:02:30,708
Interviewer: What do you mean by different?

44
00:02:30,708 --> 00:02:33,416
I’ve become afraid of people

45
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:39,500
I speak cautiously, and the words I say I must be certain of

46
00:02:39,916 --> 00:02:42,416
Interviewer: And that continued even after ISIS left?
Witness: Yes, until now

47
00:02:42,625 --> 00:02:44,583
Interviewer: And is it the same with your relationships with people?

48
00:02:45,125 --> 00:02:49,875
My relationships are just greetings and I don’t like to get close with anyone

49
00:02:49,958 --> 00:02:51,875
I’ve become quiet

50
00:02:53,125 --> 00:02:55,875
Interviewer: Is this all just a reaction?
Witness: Yes, it is

51
00:02:56,416 --> 00:02:58,000
Interviewer: And can you get rid of it?

52
00:02:58,458 --> 00:03:00,625
I ask God to let me get rid of it

53
00:03:00,875 --> 00:03:02,000
Interviewer: God willing

54
00:03:04,625 --> 00:03:07,750
Interviewer: Do you want to tell us a particular story or incident?

55
00:03:09,208 --> 00:03:13,125
That happened to you while you were in prison or while ISIS was in Mosul

56
00:03:14,458 --> 00:03:17,416
Or an image you recall now before you

57
00:03:17,625 --> 00:03:21,458
Or an incident that affected you or made you cry under ISIS

58
00:03:21,958 --> 00:03:24,458
Something that happened in front of you and made you sad and cry

59
00:03:25,375 --> 00:03:28,416
I was saddened for the people who died

60
00:03:29,708 --> 00:03:31,875
I was saddened for my house that was looted

61
00:03:33,416 --> 00:03:35,500
And I had nothing else

62
00:03:37,250 --> 00:03:38,958
And after the area was liberated

63
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:41,125
Good people came and helped us

64
00:03:42,125 --> 00:03:43,708
One brought me a fridge to help

65
00:03:43,708 --> 00:03:46,875
Another brought me a freezer, another brought me a sofa set

66
00:03:47,416 --> 00:03:49,875
I’d lost everything I owned

67
00:03:52,250 --> 00:03:56,375
And until now I rent a house, I don’t own one

68
00:03:58,833 --> 00:04:02,250
And the government has not compensated me for anything

69
00:04:03,125 --> 00:04:05,750
We’ve given up on the existing government, we’ve lost hope in them

70
00:04:06,416 --> 00:04:07,833
And thank God, Lord of the worlds

71
00:04:08,208 --> 00:04:11,125
Interviewer: You said you were saddened for your looted house

72
00:04:11,458 --> 00:04:14,125
Was it looted by ISIS?

73
00:04:14,458 --> 00:04:16,958
Or did it happen during the battle?

74
00:04:17,125 --> 00:04:18,958
Or was it looted by certain people?

75
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:21,750
How was it looted, and who did it?

76
00:04:22,125 --> 00:04:23,875
The looting that happened

77
00:04:24,250 --> 00:04:29,125
Was by ISIS and by gangs during the liberation

78
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:32,833
And my house was destroyed by shelling

79
00:04:34,583 --> 00:04:35,583
And there was looting

80
00:04:37,500 --> 00:04:41,458
Like the Ali Baba gangs and other thieves

81
00:04:41,625 --> 00:04:43,958
Interviewer: Were those who looted from Mosul?

82
00:04:44,125 --> 00:04:46,958
No, they were strangers

83
00:04:47,583 --> 00:04:50,375
Interviewer: Do you mean strangers from Mosul’s outskirts or from outside?

84
00:04:50,708 --> 00:04:52,458
From gangs that entered Mosul?

85
00:04:55,250 --> 00:04:58,416
The gangs that entered Mosul are the ones who destroyed it

86
00:04:59,083 --> 00:05:00,625
The people of Mosul did not destroy it

87
00:05:01,208 --> 00:05:04,875
Interviewer: You personally, aside from the money stolen from your house

88
00:05:04,958 --> 00:05:07,250
And the things stolen from it, and aside from prison

89
00:05:09,333 --> 00:05:11,750
What do you feel was stolen from you besides these?

90
00:05:14,750 --> 00:05:15,833
My health was stolen

91
00:05:17,833 --> 00:05:23,541
When I lost my health I lost the dearest thing I had

92
00:05:25,708 --> 00:05:28,416
And I could no longer make my family live properly

93
00:05:29,708 --> 00:05:31,125
Because there is no livelihood

94
00:05:32,416 --> 00:05:33,750
And no work like before

95
00:05:35,750 --> 00:05:42,208
Now they give me a small welfare salary, it doesn’t even cover the rent

96
00:05:45,458 --> 00:05:46,833
And our hope is in God

97
00:05:47,708 --> 00:05:49,625
Interviewer: How do you make money besides welfare now?

98
00:05:49,625 --> 00:05:50,625
I can’t work

99
00:05:50,750 --> 00:05:52,583
Interviewer: And your kids?
Witness: They are young

100
00:05:55,375 --> 00:05:56,458
They go to school

101
00:05:57,708 --> 00:06:00,708
I pulled my eldest son out of school so he could work and support me

102
00:06:02,125 --> 00:06:03,250
He is 17 years old
